As a public patient you will be treated at no charge.

Medicare does not provide benefits for the following:

* most dental examinations and treatment;
* most physiotherapy, occupational therapy, speech therapy, eye therapy, chiropractic services, podiatry or psychology services;
* acupuncture (unless part of a doctor's consultation);
* glasses and contact lenses;
* hearing aids and other appliances; andÂ
* home nursing.

You can arrange private health insurance to cover many of these services.Â
Most insurers will have limits on how much you can claim per service and per
year.

#### Medicare does not cover:

* examinations for life insurance, superannuation or memberships for which someone else is responsible (for example, a compensation insurer, employer or government authority);
* ambulance services;
* most dental examinations and treatment;
* most physiotherapy, occupational therapy, speech therapy, eye therapy, chiropractic services, podiatry orÂ psychology services;
* acupuncture (unless part of a doctor's consultation);
* glasses and contact lenses;
* hearing aids and other appliances; andÂ
* home nursing.

Many of these items can be covered on private health insurance general
treatment (extras) policies.Â Most insurers will have limits on how much you
can claim per service and per year.

### Pharmaceutical

Under the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (PBS) you pay only part of the cost
of most prescription medicines purchased at pharmacies. The rest of the cost
is covered by the PBS. You must present your Medicare card to obtain this
benefit.

